{
  "style": "IEEE",
  "texts": [
    "As discussed earlier, the grammar of text is fundamentally different from the grammar of speech (Halliday 1987(Halliday [2002]], Ong 1992) (Kalantzis andCope 2020: 50-52, Kalantzis andCope 2022).",
    "The grammar of inner speech is even more distant from text for many reasons, prominent among which is the need for explicitness if the meaning is to carry across time and space.",
    "And to the extent that inner speech is an amalgam of images-\"mindsight\" as Colin McGinn calls it (McGinn 2004)-\"imagining\" is very different from making and viewing pictures.",
    "These are huge transpositions, at once cognitive, multimodal, and materialized through work with media.",
    "So, even if there is a machine to do it for us now, writing remains an important thing to learn.Generative AI puts the narrow, utilitarian literacy pedagogies out of business, with their standardized tests to match."
  ],
